Load the datasets e0F1 and e0M1. Note: \(e_0\) is demographic notation for life expectancy at birth, or how many years, on average, a person from a specific population can expect to live. These estimates are typically made separately for two sex categories: male and female, as there is a known gap between male and female life expectancy.

data(`e0F1`)
data(`e0M1`)

(a)5 points Use several functions we’ve discussed to ‘get to know your data’. HINT: don’t forget to use the help documentation for the datasets/package.

  1. Who published these life expectancy estimates? When were they published?

Reference: World Population Prospects: The 2024 Revision. http://population.un.org/wpp

Details: These data come from the United Nations’ annual and 5-year time series of the life expectancy at birth (e0) for all countries of the world as available in 2024.

“These datasets are based on estimates and projections of United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division (2024). The pre-1950 datasets and the 5-year datasets were compiled by Patrick Gerland.”

  1. What class of object is the second column of e0F1?

The second column of e0F1 is a character column called ‘name’.

Pivot the data:

Join the data for plotting and later use:

paraguay_long_female = paraguay_long_female %>%
  mutate(Gender = "Female")
paraguay_long_male = paraguay_long_male %>%
  mutate(Gender = "Male")

joined_paraguay_data = bind_rows(paraguay_long_female, paraguay_long_male)

joined_paraguay_data$Year = as.numeric(joined_paraguay_data$Year)

Plot the data:

ggplot(joined_paraguay_data, aes(x = Year, y = e_0, color = Gender)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  ggtitle("Female and Male Life Expectancy\nin Paraguay (1950-2023)") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Life Expectancy") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("goldenrod", "seagreen")) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(joined_paraguay_data$Year), max(joined_paraguay_data$Year), by = 5)) +
geom_vline(xintercept = 2021, linetype = "dashed", color = "red", linewidth = 0.5) +
theme_minimal() +
theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 10),
    legend.title = element_blank()
  )

There’s a sharp drop in 2021 marked with a red dashed line. This was likely due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Paraguay’s response to the pandemic in 2020 and 2021 was to focus on sanitation, exposure tracking, and a multi-phase return to school/work plan beginning in October 2020.

Even with the onset of vaccinations in early 2021, that year experienced the maximum amount of deaths and infections between 2020 and when they stopped tracking this information in March of 2022. This information was found through the Paraguayan Government’s Department of Public Health and Wellness.

  1. Convert your new data.frame from wide format (one row per country) to long format (a row for every country/year period). In tidyr this is done using pivot_longer. In base R this is done using reshape. Use both pivot_longer and reshape.
cyclone_data_long <- plot_data %>%
  pivot_longer(
    # Specify the columns from years 1951 to 2023
    cols = `1950`:`2023`, 
    # name of new SINGLE column for year from MANY columns
    names_to = "Year", 
    # name of new column for life expectancy values
    values_to = "e_0"      
  )

  1. How do the two functions differ in their output?

The tidyverse function pivot_longer() outputs a tibble, while the base R reshape() function outputs a basic R dataframe. Tibbles tend to be more human-readable with cleaner presentation, but are not very different from R dataframes just from appearance alone. A bigger difference is the way the two functions differ in treating variables: the tidyverse’s output won’t make the new column values into factors like the base R’s function will.

  1. Create table showing the min, mean, and max life expectancies for each population in your dataset.
# Subsetting data for each country and population group
china_long <- subset(cyclone_data_long, name == "China")
philippines_long <- subset(cyclone_data_long, name == "Philippines")
japan_long <- subset(cyclone_data_long, name == "Japan")
mexico_long <- subset(cyclone_data_long, name == "Mexico")
world_long <- subset(cyclone_data_long, name == "World")

pop_list <- list(china_long, philippines_long, japan_long, mexico_long, world_long)

# place to store the new data
summary_e0_table <- data.frame(
  name = character(0), 
  `minimum e_0` = numeric(0), 
  `maximum e_0` = numeric(0), 
  `average e_0` = numeric(0)
)

for (populationn in pop_list) {
  pop_name <- unique(populationn$name)
  min_e0 <- min(populationn$e_0, na.rm = TRUE)
  max_e0 <- max(populationn$e_0, na.rm = TRUE)
  mean_e0 <- mean(populationn$e_0, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  summary_e0_table <- rbind(summary_e0_table, 
                            data.frame(name = pop_name, 
                                       `minimum e_0` = min_e0, 
                                       `maximum e_0` = max_e0, 
                                       `average e_0` = mean_e0))
}

kable(summary_e0_table, 
      col.names = c("Country Name", "e_0 Minimum", "e_0 Maximum","e_0 Average"),
      digits = 2,
      caption = "Female Life Expectancy at Birth in Years: Top 4 Cyclone-Prone Nations (2024) vs. World") %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 15)

This plot shows the scale of great dips in life expectancy at birth, particularly in China (red) in 1960. This was due to the Great Chinese Famine which occurred between 1959-1961 and is attributed to the Great Leap Forward by many historians. According to Wikipedia (cited by many journal articles, this being one of them) this famine is considered one of the deadliest in history.

All nations except the Philippines appear to be surpassing the World’s trends, especially from about the mid 1970s onward.

Description: Mutating joins add columns from y to x, matching observations based on the keys. There are four mutating joins: the inner join, and the three outer joins.

Inner join: An inner_join() only keeps observations from x that have a matching key in y. This means that generally inner joins are not appropriate in most analyses, because it is too easy to lose observations.

Outer joins: The three outer joins keep observations that appear in at least one of the data frames:

A left_join() keeps all observations in x.

A right_join() keeps all observations in y.

A full_join() keeps all observations in x and y.

(a)10 points Use one of these functions to create a new data.frame called e0 that contains all information from e0F1 and e0M1. Pivot the data.frame longer to create an object called e0_long so that there is a new column called Sex indicating whether the row contains life expectancies for “Female” or “Male”.

Because the question is asking for all information from e0F1 and e0M1 I will use full_join before pivoting.

I am including information about using regex to grab the year columns affected by the pivot by using the following, but not using it in the code below:

  1. ^: Matches the start of the string.
  2. [0-9]: Matches any digit (0–9).
  3. {4}: Matches exactly 4 digits (e.g., 1950, 2023).
  4. \.: Matches a literal period (.). The \ is needed to escape the ‘.’ in regex, as ‘.’ is like a wild card and can match any character.
  5. (x|y): Matches either x or y. This is a group using the | operator (OR).
  6. $: Matches the end of the string.

It’s easier to use the select function because it is convenient, but that is also more hard-coded than using regex, so I’m including it as a comment in the code in case it’s useful to me later.

# Full Join the two dataframes together
e0 <- full_join(e0F1, e0M1, by = "country_code")
e0 = e0 %>% select(-name.y)
e0 = e0 %>% rename(name = name.x) 
# e0

The reason I chose not to present the entire e0_long dataframe, even with a Kable-style table, is because it is so large that the document fails to render.

e0_long <- e0 %>%
  pivot_longer(
    # cols = matches("^[0-9]{4}\\.(x|y)$") would also work
    cols = -c(country_code, name), 
    names_to = c("year", "sex"),
    names_sep = "\\.",
    values_to = "e_0"
  )%>%
  # Map 'x' and 'y' to 'Female' and 'Male'
  mutate(
    sex = ifelse(sex == "x", "Female", "Male") 
  )
